n]]\n| runtime       = 24\u201326 minutes\n| network       = [[Discovery Channel]] (2005\u201312, 2017\u201318)<br>[[Bravo (American TV channel)|Bravo]] (2019)\n| first_aired   = {{Start date|2005|12|5}}\n| last_aired    = present\n| related       = ''[[Cash Cab (British game show)|Cash Cab]]''\n| website       = https://www.discovery.com/tv-shows/cash-cab/\n| website_title = Official website\n}}\n'''''Cash Cab''''' (stylized as '''''CA$H CAB''''')<ref>{{cite web|url= http://monsterscifishow.files.wordpress.com/2007/08/cashcab.jpg|title= Cash Cab logo}}</ref> is an American [[game show]] that aired new episodes on the [[Discovery Channel]] from 2005 to 2012, with new seasons also in 2017 and 2018. It began airing on December 5, 2005, hosted by stand-up comedian [[Ben Bailey]], and aired its last episode on September 28, 2012. The show was revived on December 4, 2017. It is part of the global ''[[Cash Cab (British game show)|Cash Cab]]'' franchise that originated in the United Kingdom.\n\nWhile Bailey's show took place in New York City, some episodes of season six took place in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]].  Contestants who ultimately hailed the Cash Cab were not made aware that they were part of the game until they hired the cab and Bailey informed them of the show and its rules.\n\nOn August 8, 2007, Discovery Channel began airing a [[spin-off (media)|spin-off]] edition of the program, ''Cash Cab: After Dark'', in which contestants were picked up near or after sunset as well as overnight and the cash value of the questions was double that of the regular version of the show. The questions were usually more difficult than the daytime version.\n\nOn September 19, 2019, it was announced that the series would be revived. It premiered on October 7, 2019 on [[Bravo (American TV channel)|Bravo]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Bravo Is Reviving the Popular Emmy Award-Winning Gameshow \"Cash Cab\" from Lion Television|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2019/07/02/bravo-is-reviving-the-popular-emmy-award-winning-gameshow-cash-cab-from-lion-television-213110/20190702bravo01/|work=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=July 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bravo's Revival of Popular Gameshow \"Cash Cab\" Premieres Monday, October 7 at 11:30PM ET/PT|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2019/09/19/bravos-revival-of-popular-gameshow-cash-cab-premieres-monday-october-7-at-1130pm-et-pt-136414/20190919bravo01/|work=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=September 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bravotv.com/cash-cab/episode-guide|title=Episode Guide {{!}} Cash Cab|date=2019-09-19|website=Bravo TV Official Site|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-25}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcast history==\nAccording to ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', Discovery Channel initially ordered 40 episodes from Lion Television (with Executive Producers Tom Cohen, Allison Corn, and Tony Tackaberry with Ben Bailey being the most recent) and taping of the initial run was completed in November 2005 before the show premiered that December.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2005/scene/news/lion-tv-strikes-it-rich-with-format-shows-1117933650|title=Lion TV strikes it rich with format shows|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=November 29, 2005}}</ref> A new set of 40 episodes were taped and aired in 2006 and 2007. Another 80 episodes were taped in 2007 and aired through spring and summer. Another 40 episodes were taped and aired in 2008 and 2009. Another 40 episodes were taped for airing in 2010 and 2011.\n\nThe sixth season premiered on February 14, 2011, at 6:00 p.m. E/P. During a hiatus, Ben Bailey did a standup special recounting his time as host of the show. He correctly stated in the special that the show has been cancelled for the last two years (taping for the then-current series wrapped in 2008), however, a renewal offer was made after the standup concert was taped during 2011 returning the show to the schedule. The seventh season premiered Thursday, January 5, 2012, at 6:00 p.m. E/P with two half-hour episodes.\n\nOn April 18, 2012, it was announced that ''Cash Cab'' would end its 6-year run.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2012/04/the-end-of-the-road-for-cash-cab.html|title=It's the End of the Road for Cash Cab|last=Adalian|first=Josef|work=Vulture|publisher=New York Media LLC|date=April 18, 2012|accessdate=April 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, 2017, ''[[Discovery Channel|Discovery]]'' announced it was working on episodes that will feature \"appearances from notables in comedy, film, and TV\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/cash-cab-revival-discovery-david-steinberg-1202016938/|last=Schwindt|first=Oriana|title=Discovery to Resurrect \u2018Cash Cab\u2019 Game Show|magazine=Variety|date=March 27, 2017}}</ref> On June 5, 2017, original host Ben Bailey confirmed he would return for a new season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/ben-bailey-hosts-cash-cab-revival-discovery-series-1202107526/|title=\u2018Cash Cab\u2019: Ben Bailey Returns To Host Discovery\u2019s Series Revival|last=Pederson|first=Erik|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=June 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/RealBenBailey/posts/1642811532426430|title=Ben Bailey - Posts|author=Ben Bailey|publisher=[[Facebook]]|date=June 5, 2017}}</ref> Season 8, which also aired on Discovery, premiered on December 4, 2017.\n\nOn May 14, 2018, Discovery announced that Season 9 would be returning in July 2018. Season 9 premiered on July 27, 2018 with a special [[Shark Week]] episode to coincide with the 30th Anniversary of Shark Week.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/cash-cab-renewed-at-discovery-channel-1111515/|title='Cash Cab' Renewed at Discovery Channel (Exclusive)|last=Nordyke|first=Kimberly|magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=May 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Rules==\nWhen the potential contestants enter the cab and state their destination, they are made aware that they are in the Cash Cab as ceiling lights and a fanfare plays inside, accompanied by the host's greeting.  While the only rules given on-camera after the introduction and before asking \"Do you want to play?\" pertain to his or her driving and the \"three strikes and you're out\" rule, the contestants are also informed that once their traveling begins, the cab will not take detours of any kind unless directed by a police officer, stop sign, traffic light or other legal means of diverting traffic. Bailey or Melewski offers them the chance to get out of the cab if they do not wish to play, and contestants who choose to play the game must stay in the cab until they reach their destination or get three strikes.\n\nFor the first season, the first five questions were worth $25 each, the next five questions were worth $50 each, and any question thereafter was worth $100. For the second season, the first four questions were worth $25 each, the next four were worth $50 each, and the ninth and succeeding questions were worth $100. In ''Cash Cab: After Dark'' - and beginning with the regular episodes of Season 3 - all of the money values were doubled to $50, $100, and $200. Beginning in the fourth season, some games were designated as Double Ride games, making the question values $100, $200, and $400.\n\nEach wrong answer earns the contestant(s) a strike. On the third strike, they forfeit all their winnings and Bailey or Melewski will immediately pull over and kick them out of the cab. Once players have exited the Cash Cab, a camera crew from the trailing production van is already on the street waiting to tape their departure.\n\n===Red Light Challenge===\nWhen a contestant has won at least $200 or $300 in a normal game or an After Dark game - or at least $400 or $600 on a Double Ride, and the cab is forced to stop at a traffic light, Bailey or Melewski will announce a Red Light Challenge. He or she reads a question that has multiple correct answers usually four to seven and the passenger(s) have 30 seconds to give those answers; they do not always have to give all of the answers. Since there is no penalty for an incorrect answer, giving all the correct answers in the allotted time is worth $250 or $500 during Double Ride games regardless of how many incorrect answers a contestant might also blurt out along the way. The contestant does not receive the extra $250 (or $500) if the 30-second time limit runs out; it is also not counted as a strike, and the contestant doesn't lose any accumulated money. While only one Red Light Challenge is usually played per game, beginning in Season 4 there are multiple Red Light Challenges during certain games at least two per game with the second for accumulating at least $1,000 in revival season it was sponsored by Cash app\n\n===Shout-Outs===\nContestants have two forms of help known as \"Shout-Outs\" at their disposal during the game; each can be used only once, and neither may be used on a Red Light Challenge or a Video Bonus. In the Mobile Shout-Out, the contestant makes a phone call to someone they choose by means of a cell phone either provided by Bailey or Melewski or one belonging to a contestant if they have one. The call can take up to a maximum of 15 seconds before the contestant has to give an answer, with the result being either additional money or a strike. The contestant may also elect to use a Street Shout-Out, in which Bailey or Melewski immediately pulls the cab to a curb so that anyone on the sidewalk can be asked for help, without any official time limit. A second Street Shout-Out is included on a Double Ride meaning they can ask another person but no second Mobile Shout-out meaning they can't call another person. In the revived Cash Cab, the Mobile Shout-Out was replaced by the Social Media Shout-Out, in which Ben activates Facebook Live so that those on the site may help the contestant.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://people.com/tv/cash-cab-back-discovery-channel/|title=Cash Cab Is Coming Back to TV (with Celebrity Guests!) Host Ben Bailey Dishes on Everything New|last=Calfas|first=Jennifer|magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=December 1, 2017|accessdate=December 6, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Video Bonus===\nShould the passenger(s) reach the destination without striking out, Bailey/Melewski offers a choice: the option of leaving the cab and keeping the prize money that they have won, or they can stay and try to double their money by risking it all on a Video Bonus question. Bailey/Melewski plays a video clip and asks the contestant(s) a single question based on its content. If the question is answered correctly, the contestant(s) win double what they have earned so far, but if they are wrong, they lose all of their money \"at the very last moment\", as Bailey says, and \"leave with nothing but a cab ride\".\n\nUnlike some other versions of the game, U.S. contestants who decline to attempt the Video Bonus are not shown the question they would have been asked.\n\n===Double Ride===\nBeginning in Season 4, this rarely occurring part of the show happens when randomly selected passengers are able to win double the amount of money of a normal game. The first four questions are worth $100, the second four are worth $200 and the rest until the end of the game are worth $400. The \"Red Light Challenge\" is worth $500.\n\n==Record payouts==\nThe current record of $6,200 won on one ride is held by Sam Meyer (riding solo, on a Double Ride, taking and winning the Double-or-Nothing Video Bonus question) on the episode that aired May 18, 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB121443709962505255?mod=opinion_journal_leisure_art|title= He Drives This Game-Show Vehicle|newspaper = The Wall Street Journal | first=Joanne | last=Kaufman | date=June 26, 2008}}</ref> This topped the old record held by contestants Sean Devney and Steve Irolla, two New York City tour guides who won $4,100 after answering the \"Video Bonus\" question correctly. They reached their final destination with two strikes (both on $200 questions).\n\n==Special editions==\nOne episode of the program was a special celebrity edition, featuring actor [[Thomas Haden Church]] of ''[[Spider-Man 3]]'', [[National Hockey League|NHL]] players [[Jed Ortmeyer]] and [[Ryan Hollweg]] of the [[New York Rangers]] and journalist [[Harry Smith (US journalist)|Harry Smith]], formerly of [[CBS]]' ''[[The Early Show]]''. All played for a charity of their choice, and Discovery Channel matched the contestants' winnings. Another episode was a special in which the passengers were asked questions relating to the 2008 film ''[[Frost/Nixon (film)|Frost/Nixon]]''. In this episode, the host of ''[[Cash Cab (Canadian game show)|Cash Cab: Canada]]'', [[Adam Growe]], was driving the cab instead of [[Ben Bailey]].\n\nOn April 21, 2009, Discovery aired a charity episode of ''Cash Cab'' for its 250th episode featuring two rides by boat crew members from ''[[Deadliest Catch]]''. ''[[FV Time Bandit|Time Bandit]]'' co-captain Andy Hillstrand and Josh Harris, son of ''[[FV Cornelia Marie|Cornelia Marie]]'' captain [[Phil Harris (fisherman)|Phil Harris]], went against [[Sig Hansen]] (captain of the [[FV Northwestern|''Northwestern'']]) and his two brothers. All cash values were doubled from the Season 3 payouts, the passengers received a second Street Shout-Out, and all money earned was donated by the passengers to the charities of their choice.\n\nIn the ''Cash Cab: Las Vegas'' episodes, filmed in May 2010 and broadcast beginning in August of that year,<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.vegaschatter.com/story/2010/8/9/114010/3894/vegas-travel/Cash+Cab+Shouts+Out+To+Vegas+Tonightl?mod=art|title= Cash Cab Shouts Out To Vegas Tonight|publisher = Vegas Chatter | date=August 9, 2010}}</ref> celebrities play for charity and civilians play for themselves. Guests have included [[Mayor of Las Vegas]], [[Oscar Goodman]], comedian [[David Brenner]], the band [[Neon Trees]] and magicians [[Penn & Teller]]. The prizes are sometimes doubled in a \"[[Blackjack#Player decisions|Double Down]] Ride\", just like on the regular show. In the event they strike out or miss the Video Bonus question, their charities receive $500, though some celebrities decide to also chip in with the amount of money lost, out of their own pockets.{{citation needed|date=August 2010}}\n\nOn December 4, 2017, Discovery aired a special Celebrity Edition, where as the unsuspecting passengers hailed the Cash Cab, they were joined by celebrities to help them, featuring ''[[NCIS: New Orleans]]'' actor Scott Bakula, actor & comedian [[Gilbert Gottfried]], and ''[[Friends]]'' actor Matthew Perry.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2017/11/28/cash-cab-ben-bailey-discovery-celebrities-revival/887237001/|title=The meter is running again: We climb into the 'Cash Cab' with Ben Bailey|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2017-12-06|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Taglines==\nThe show's tagline in the first two seasons was: \"There are 13,000 cabs in New York City, but there's only ''one'' that pays ''you''!\" Starting in season three, the tagline was modified: \"There are 13,000 cabs in the streets of the Big Apple, but there's only ''one'' that pays ''you''!\" On ''Cash Cab: After Dark'', the tagline is: \"Every night, 13,000 cabs hit the streets of the city that never sleeps, but there's only ''one'' that pays ''you''!\"\n\n==''Cash Cab: Chicago''==\nDuring Season 6 of ''Cash Cab'', a new spin-off series, ''Cash Cab: Chicago'', hosted by comedian Beth Melewski and using the same rules as its New York counterpart, aired. The spin-off was cancelled after one season, but rerun episodes are aired along with ''Cash Cab'' episodes in syndication.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.suntimes.com/entertainment/television/8579723-421/end-of-the-road-for-cash-cab-chicago.html | work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|title=End of the road for 'Cash Cab Chicago' | date=April 5, 2012}}</ref> Ben Bailey stated that the show was created during contract renewal negotiations.<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MNjlVkDCJZc|title=Episode #103 - Ben Bailey & ME (FULL EPISODE)|date=30 November 2014|work=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nA support van tails the Cash Cab, containing producers and a camera crew for the various street shots. The staff provide logistical information and questions by way of a walkie-talkie and earpiece worn by the host. The Cash Cab is equipped with ten cameras: one on the host, three on the passengers, one pointing forward from the back window of the cab, and three (front, left and right) in the advertising shell on the roof of the cab showing the passing streetscape. The rear of the cab behind the seats contains ten recording decks and other production equipment.\n\nThe lighting and the music that go off when contestants enter the cab consist of a switchboard that is connected to an [[iPod]] and the car stereo. The Video Bonus monitor is a DVD player that is embedded to the back of the front passenger seat.\n\nSome contestants are randomly picked as they walk along the sidewalk, while others are selected in advance. Even so, those picked in advance are told that the cab is supposed to take them to the show on which they will appear. The cab turns out to be the show itself.<ref name=\"''Cash Cab'' Can Be a Lucrative Ride\">{{cite web|url= https://www.today.com/popculture/cash-cab-can-be-lucrative-ride-wbna12055144|title= ''Cash Cab'' Can Be a Lucrative Ride|publisher = Today.com}}</ref>\n\nNear the end of the game at the player's destination [[Ben Bailey]] or Beth Melewski appears to present the [[cash]] won. In reality, this cash is a [[Theatrical property|prop]] and used for on-air purposes only. The winnings, which must be taxed, are sent via check.<ref name=\"''Cash Cab'' Can Be a Lucrative Ride\"/>\n\nThe Cash Cab in New York is a [[Toyota Sienna]] minivan<ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB121443709962505255|title = He Drives This Game-Show Vehicle | newspaper = The Wall Street Journal|first= Joanne|last = Kaufmann|date=June 26, 2008|accessdate=April 30, 2009}}</ref> with the [[Taxicabs of New York City|New York City Taxi and Limousine Commission]] call sign \"1G12\" in the first two seasons and during the After Dark shows. A new cab with the call sign of \"7N78\" has been used since, which also features new headliner lighting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avsforum.com/avs-vb/showthread.php?p=14506841 |title=\"Cash Cab\" on Discovery HD |publisher=Avsforum.com |date= |accessdate=2013-10-23}}</ref>  In Season 8 and 9, the call sign of the cab has been \"31Z8\". In season 10, the vehicle was updated, and the call sign of the cab has been \"47J2\".\n\nBeth Melewski Host of The Discovery Channel's spin-off from Cash Cab called Cash Cab, Chicago. It too also is a Toyota Sienna minivan with the Yellow Taxi call sign \"4472\".\n\n==Broadcast and syndication==\nAs of March 2017, reruns air on [[Cozi TV]] and on [[Game Show Network]]. The New York City version reruns air on the Quest network in the UK. On October 26, 2009, [[MGM Television]] announced that the reruns would begin airing on local stations in September 2010.<ref>[http://www.marketwatch.com/story/mgm-domestic-television-to-launch-discovery-channels-hit-series-cash-cab-into-us-syndication-2009-10-26 MGM Domestic Television to Launch Discovery Channel's Hit Series \"CASH CAB\" Into U.S. Syndication], October 26, 2009.</ref> Stations are allowed the option to air the series as a daily strip or as a weekend series. [[Game Show Network|GSN]] began airing the series starting on March 13, 2017.\n\nOn March 27, 2017, Discovery announced it was working on new episodes that will feature guest hosts from \"the worlds of comedy, film and TV\" as the drivers. Despite initial reports that he would not return,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv/cash-cab-reboot-coming-discovery-channel-ben-bailey-article-1.3010890|title=''Cash Cab'' reboot coming to Discovery Channel without Ben Bailey|work=New York Daily News|last=Feldman|first=Kate|date=March 27, 2017|accessdate=June 5, 2017}}</ref> Bailey did host the revival episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/ben-bailey-cash-cab-discovery/|title=Ben Bailey to Return as Host for Discovery's Revamped ''Cash Cab''|work=The Wrap|last=Maglio|first=Tony|date=June 5, 2017|accessdate=June 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn July 27, 2018, a new season of Cash Cab premiered, also hosted by Ben Bailey. The first episode of the new season had a [[Shark Week]] theme.\n\n==Accolades==\nBailey has been nominated four times for the [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Game Show Host]], winning the award in 2010, 2011 and 2013. ''Cash Cab'' won the [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Game/Audience Participation Show|Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Game Show]] in 2008, 2009 and 2010. In 2013, the show appeared in ''[[TV Guide]]''{{'}}s list of the 60 greatest game shows ever.<ref name=TVGuide>Fretts, Bruce (June 17, 2013). \"Eyes on the Prize\", ''[[TV Guide]]'', pp. 14 and 15.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Taxicab Confessions]]''\n* ''[[BrainRush]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2010}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://dsc.discovery.com/fansites/cashcab/cashcab.html Official Discovery Channel ''Cash Cab'' website]\n*{{tv.com show|cash-cab|Cash Cab}}\n*{{IMDb title|0790825|Cash Cab}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|before = [[The Price Is Right (American game show)|The Price Is Right]]|title = [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Game/Audience Participation Show]]|years = 2008\u20132010|after = [[Jeopardy!]] and [[Wheel of Fortune (American game show)|Wheel of Fortune]] (tie)}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Daytime Emmy Award Outstanding Game/Audience Participation Show}}\n{{Discovery Channel programming}}\n{{Bravo programming}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cash Cab}}\n[[Category:2000s American game shows]]\n[[Category:2005 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s American game shows]]\n[[Category:2012 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:2017 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:American television series based on British television series]]\n[[Category:American television series revived after cancellation]]\n[[Category:Bravo (American TV channel) original programming]]\n[[Category:Cash Cab]]\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Game Show winners]]\n[[Category:Discovery Channel original programming]]\n[[Category:ProSieben television series<!-- Puls 4 -->]]\n[[Category:RedeTV! programmes]]\n[[Category:Taxicabs]]\n[[Category:Television programmes on Channel 2 (Israel)]]\n[[Category:Television series by MGM Television]]\n[[Category:V (TV network) shows]]\n", "name_user": "Kenneth Eugene Jack aka Wolfman Jack", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProduction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cash_Cab_(American_game_show)"}
