{"title_page": "The Injury", "text_new": "{{Infobox television episode\n| series       =[[The Office (American TV series)|The Office]]\n| season       =2\n| episode      =12\n| airdate      =January 12, 2006\n| production   =2011<ref name=\"prodnumbers\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/office/listings/|title=Shows A\u2013Z \u2013 Office, The on NBC|work=The Futon Critic|accessdate=January 25, 2013}}</ref>\n| director     =[[Bryan Gordon]]\n| writer       =[[Mindy Kaling]]\n| photographer =[[Randall Einhorn]]\n| editor       =[[Dean Holland]]\n| length = 22 minutes\n| guests       = *[[Leslie David Baker]] as [[Stanley Hudson]]\n*[[Brian Baumgartner]] as [[Kevin Malone]]\n*[[Kate Flannery]] as [[Meredith Palmer]]\n*[[Angela Kinsey]] as [[Angela Martin]]\n*[[Oscar Nunez]] as [[Oscar Martinez (The Office)|Oscar Martinez]]\n*[[Phyllis Smith]] as [[Phyllis Vance|Phyllis Lapin]]\n*Marcus A. York as [[List of The Office (American TV series) characters#Billy Merchant|Billy Merchant]]\n| season_article = The Office (American season 2)\n| episode_list =List of The Office (American TV series) episodes\n| prev         =[[Booze Cruise (The Office)|Booze Cruise]]\n| next         =[[The Secret (The Office)|The Secret]]\n}}\n\n\"'''The Injury'''\" is the twelfth episode of the [[The Office (U.S. season 2)|second season]] of the American [[comedy]] [[television program|television series]] ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]'', and the show's eighteenth episode overall. The episode was written by [[Mindy Kaling]], who also acts in the show as [[Kelly Kapoor]], and directed by [[Bryan Gordon]]. \"The Injury\" first aired in the United States on January 12, 2006 on [[NBC]]. The episode guest starred Marcus York as [[List of characters from The Office (US T.V. series)#Billy Merchant|Billy Merchant]].\n\nThe series depicts the everyday lives of office employees in the [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]] branch of the fictional [[Dunder Mifflin]] Paper Company. In the episode, [[Michael Scott (The Office)|Michael Scott]] ([[Steve Carell]]) accidentally burns his foot on his [[George Foreman Grill]], but insists on coming to work anyway. When none of his employees, except for [[Dwight Schrute]] ([[Rainn Wilson]]), help him, Michael feels under-appreciated. Meanwhile, Dwight starts acting strangely nice to everyone, especially [[Pam Beesly]] ([[Jenna Fischer]]).\n\n\"The Injury\" was originally conceived by [[Greg Daniels]] to be a humorous follow-up to the previous episode, \"[[Booze Cruise (The Office)|Booze Cruise]]\". According to [[B. J. Novak]], the episode started out as an idea in the writing room that just \"spun out of control\". The episode was originally going to be called \"My Grilled Foot\", but it was later changed when the writers decided the name was \"too weird\". \"The Injury\" received widespread acclaim from critics and is widely regarded by critics as one of the show's greatest episodes. The episode earned a Nielsen rating of 5.1 in the 18\u201349 demographic and was viewed by 10.3 million viewers, making it, at the time, the highest-rated episode of the series.\n\n==Plot==\n[[Michael Scott (The Office)|Michael Scott]] ([[Steve Carell]]) accidentally burns his foot while grilling [[bacon]] on his [[George Foreman Grill]], which he keeps next to his bed. After he makes a distress call to the office, [[Dwight Schrute]] ([[Rainn Wilson]]) comes to \"rescue\" him, but crashes his car into [[gatepost|a pole]]. Dwight becomes more easygoing and friendly to his co-workers. He and [[Pam Beesly]] ([[Jenna Fischer]]) strike up a friendship as a result.\n\nMichael becomes upset with the staff's lack of compassion towards his \"disability\", and brings in [[List of characters from The Office (US T.V. series)#Billy Merchant|Billy Merchant]] (Marcus A. York), the building's property manager who uses a [[wheelchair]], to discuss what it is like to be disabled. Billy leaves after Michael makes several offensive remarks, but not before pointing out to [[Jim Halpert]] ([[John Krasinski]]) that Dwight has suffered a [[concussion]] from his car crash.\n\nJim and Michael take Dwight to the hospital, where Michael insists that his burned foot is a more serious injury than Dwight's. Before they go, Pam bids \"goodbye\" to the concussed Dwight, aware that she will probably never see the good-natured version of Dwight Schrute ever again.\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Mindy Kaling at PaleyFest 2013.jpg|The episode was written by [[Mindy Kaling]], who called the episode her favorite that she had written.|200px|thumb|right]]\n\nThis episode was the second episode of the series directed by [[Bryan Gordon]].<ref name=\"episode\">{{Cite episode | title = The Injury | series = The Office | serieslink = The Office (U.S. TV series) | credits = [[Mindy Kaling]] (writer), [[Bryan Gordon]] (director) | network = NBC | airdate = January 12, 2006 | season = 2 | number = 12}}</ref> Gordon had previously directed the [[The Office (U.S. season 1)|first season]] episode \"[[The Alliance (The Office)|The Alliance]]\".<ref name=\"DVD2\">{{cite DVD notes |title=The Office: The Complete First Season |titlelink=The Office (American season 1) |origyear=2005 |others=[[Ken Kwapis]], et al |type=on-screen |publisher=[[NBC]]}}</ref> \"The Injury\" was written by [[Mindy Kaling]], who also acts for the show as customer service representative [[Kelly Kapoor]].<ref name=\"Mindy.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbc.com/The_Office/bios/mindy_kaling.shtml|title=Mindy Kaling|accessdate=June 26, 2008|last=|first=|coauthors=|date=|work=|publisher=NBC.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618054824/http://www.nbc.com/The_Office/bios/mindy_kaling.shtml|archivedate=June 18, 2008|df=}}</ref> After the character development that had occurred in the previous episode, \"[[Booze Cruise (The Office)|Booze Cruise]]\", Greg Daniels decided to create a more inane episode that involved \"Michael's grilled foot.\"<ref name=\"Convention\"/>\n\nWriter and actor [[B. J. Novak]] said the idea for \"Injury\" started out as an idea in the writing room that just \"spun out of control\".<ref name=\"Katy\">{{cite web|title=Katy Meets B.J.|url=http://www.officetally.com/bj-novak-duquesne-university|publisher=OfficeTally|accessdate=June 16, 2012|date=April 1, 2007}}</ref> The original plan was for Michael to have fallen asleep in the sun, while having sunblock all over him, except for his foot. According to BJ Novak, the episode was originally going to be called \"My Grilled Foot\", but writer Mindy Kaling thought it was \"too weird for people to tune in and watch that\".<ref name=\"Convention\">{{cite interview |last = The Office Cast|first = |title = The Office Convention 2007 Cast Q&A |year = 2007| location = ''The Office: Overtime'' | publisher = [[NBC]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=B.J. Novak answer 'Chair Model' questions|url=http://www.officetally.com/bj-novak-answers-chair-model-questions|publisher=OfficeTally|accessdate=13 December 2011}}</ref> Novak has described \"The Injury\" as one of his favorite episodes, and said of it, \"I don't think any other TV show would have made an episode from that starting point, and yet it was one of the funniest and most relatable episodes as it went on that we've ever had.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Yo |first=Michael |title=''The Office'': \"This Is Their Wedding Episode\" |work=[[E!]] |date=2009-04-30 |url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/watch_with_kristin/b121452_office_this_their_wedding_episode.html |accessdate=2009-05-17}}</ref>\n\nThe episode guest starred Marcus York, as the \"no-nonsense\" building manager for the Scranton business park. York described his character as \"just trying to do his job\".<ref name=interviewwithbilly/> York recalls being nervous during filming, and \"drawing a blank\" on his lines during the first 'run-through', because of his anxiousness around the cast members, but soon Marcus \"smoothed-out\".<ref name=\"TwoCents\">{{cite web|author=York, Marcus|date=June 16, 2006|url=http://keithp23.blogspot.com/2007/08/two-cents-five-questions-with_23.html|title=Two Cents & Five Questions With...|work=The Two Cents|accessdate=June 16, 2008}}</ref> After his portrayal of the character, York received several positive fan letters, who praised his performance as the straight man in a hectic work environment.<ref name=interviewwithbilly>{{cite magazine|last=Benet|first=Lorenzo|title=The Office Star's Own Health-Care Reform Mission|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20351156,00.html|magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=June 16, 2012|date=March 14, 2010}}</ref> John Krasinski said that the van scene was his favorite to shoot, and that it \"will go down in history as one of the most fun moments I've ever been a part of\".<ref name=\"Krasinski\">{{cite web|author=Krasinski, John|date=June 16, 2006|url=http://www.officetally.com/john-krasinski-chat-transcript|title=John Krasinski chat transcript|work=OfficeTally|accessdate=June 16, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural references==\nMichael reveals that he burned his foot on a [[George Foreman Grill]], a product promoted by [[George Foreman]], a former champion [[boxing|boxer]]. The \"Prism DuroSport\" that Pam received from Roy as a Christmas present serves as a [[Counterfeit consumer goods|knock off]] of the popular music device, the [[iPod]]. When Michael asks the office what his foot looks like, Stanley replies, \"[[Mail Boxes Etc.]]\", a reference to the name of a company absorbed by [[United Parcel Service|UPS]] in 2001.<ref name=\"Giant\"/>\n\nDuring Michael's seminar on famous disabled people, two pictures on the wall are of [[Tom Hanks]]: one from the 1994 film ''[[Forrest Gump]]'', and one from the 1988 film ''[[Big (film)|Big]]'', which Michael confuses for the 1993 film ''[[Philadelphia (film)|Philadelphia]]''.<ref name=\"Giant\"/><ref name=quotes>{{cite web|title=Michael Scott Quotes|url=http://www.tvfanatic.com/quotes/characters/michael-scott/page-92.html|publisher=TV Fanatic|accessdate=June 16, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131026150403/http://www.tvfanatic.com/quotes/characters/michael-scott/page-92.html|archive-date=October 26, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> During the scene, Kelly also name-drops [[Robert Loggia]]. In an attempt to get Dwight into Meredith's van, Jim tells him that they are going to [[Chuck E. Cheese]], to which Michael replies that he is \"so sick of\" the restaurant.<ref name=\"episode\"/>\n\n==Reception==\n\"The Injury\" originally aired on NBC in the United States on January 12, 2006.<ref name=seasontwoeps>{{cite web|title=The Office \u2013 Seasons \u2013 Season 2 \u2013 Episode Guide |url=http://www.nbc.com/the-office/episode-guide/season-2/58601/1/16/newest/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707145339/http://www.nbc.com/the-office/episode-guide/season-2/58601/1/16/newest/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 7, 2011 |publisher=[[NBC]] |accessdate=June 13, 2012 |df= }}</ref> The episode received a 5.1 rating/12% share among adults between the ages of 18 and 49. This means that it was seen by 5.1% of all 18- to 49-year-olds, and 12% of all 18- to 49-year-olds watching television at the time of the broadcast. The episode ranked as the third half-hour comedy during the week of January 16, and the series ranked as the fifteenth-highest-rated series out of 113 others, in the 18\u201349 demographic.<ref name=\"ratings\">{{cite press release |title=Jan. 18, 2006 Press Release (\"The Injury\")| archiveurl =http://www.officetally.com/the-office-nielsen-ratings/3| archivedate =October 10, 2008|url= http://nbcumv.com/release_detail.nbc/entertainment-20060118000000-nbcprimetimeresult.html|publisher=NBC|date=February 27, 2007|accessdate=June 12, 2012}}</ref> The episode was viewed by 10.3 million viewers,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Collins|first=Scott|title=NBC Enjoyed Thursday Night|journal=Los Angeles Times|date=January 13, 2006}}</ref> making it the highest-rated episode of ''The Office'' at the time, beating the series' [[Pilot (The Office)|pilot]], which received a Nielsen rating of only 5.0.<ref>[http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/ustv/a20222/american-office-an-early-ratings-hit.html  American 'Office' an early ratings hit] ''Digital Spy'', retrieved February 28, 2008</ref>\n\nAn encore presentation of the episode, on July 5, 2006, received a 1.8/6 rating and was viewed by over 3.9 million viewers: an increase by 29 percent of its lead-in audience.<ref name=\"ratings2\">{{cite press release |title=July 5, 2006 Press Release (\"Christmas Party,\" \"The Injury\")| archiveurl =http://www.officetally.com/the-office-nielsen-ratings/3| archivedate =October 10, 2008|url=http://nbcumv.com/release_detail.nbc/entertainment-20060705000000-039america039s.html|publisher=NBC|date=February 27, 2007|accessdate=June 12, 2012}}</ref> Another encore presentation on August 22, 2006 received a 2.0/6 rating, was viewed by 5.3 million viewers, retained 100 percent of its lead-in \"[[My Name is Earl]]\" audience, and ranked as the most-watched episode of ''The Office'' during the summer of 2006.<ref name=\"ratings3\">{{cite press release |title=Aug. 22, 2006 Press Release (\"The Injury\")| archiveurl =http://www.officetally.com/the-office-nielsen-ratings/3| archivedate =October 10, 2008|url=http://nbcumv.com/release_detail.nbc/entertainment-20060822000000-it039sagrandfi.html|publisher=NBC|date=February 27, 2007|accessdate=June 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSince its airing, \"The Injury\" has received critical acclaim from television critics. The scene featuring Dwight crashing his car received specific attention. ''[[IGN]]'' ranked the scene with Dwight getting in a car accident as its seventh-best moment in the first two seasons, noting that \"[t]he fact that this show can get such inspired and unusual comedy from what is essentially a puke joke is a testament to how clever ''The Office'' is.\"<ref name=\"Goldman\">Goldman, Eric & Zoromski, Brian (September 20, 2006) [http://tv.ign.com/articles/733/733879p1.html The Top 10 Moments from ''The Office''] ''[[IGN]]'', Retrieved June 16, 2008</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' named the same scene as the twentieth-funniest in ''The Office''{{'}}s first three seasons.<ref name=\"Thomas\">Thomas, Lindsey (October 17, 2007) [https://web.archive.org/web/20071020030009/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/16955952/the_25_greatest_moments_from_the_office/4 The 25 Greatest Moments from ''The Office''] ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', Retrieved June 16, 2008. Archived from [https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/16955952/the_25_greatest_moments_from_the_office/4 the original] on October 20, 2007.</ref> [[TV Squad]]'s Michael Sciannamea said that \"The Injury\" was \"another solid episode\" and that the \"show gets better with each and every week.\"<ref name=\"Sciannamea\">Sciannamea, Michael (January 13, 2006) [http://www.tvsquad.com/2006/01/13/the-office-the-injury/ ''The Office'': \"The Injury\"] TV Squad, Retrieved June 16, 2008</ref> M. Giant of [[Television Without Pity]] graded the episode with an \"A\u2013\".<ref name=\"Giant\">{{cite web|last=Giant|first=M.|date=January 12, 2006|url=http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/show/the_office/the_injury.php|title=The Injury|publisher=[[Television Without Pity]]|accessdate=June 17, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080421030324/http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/show/the_office/the_injury.php|archivedate=April 21, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> Francis Rizzo III from [[DVD Talk]] wrote positively of the episode and praised the performance of [[Rainn Wilson]] as Dwight and wrote that \"nothing he does compares\" to his performance in \"The Injury\". He called Wilson's performance as Dwight \"flat-out strange\" and noted that the episode, along with several others, \"wouldn't be nearly as entertaining\" without his character.<ref name=dvdtalk>{{cite web|last=Rizzo III|first=Francis|title=The Office \u2013 Season Two|url=http://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/23501/office-season-two-the/|publisher=[[DVD Talk]]|accessdate=June 12, 2012|date=September 12, 2006}}</ref> Mindy Kaling later stated in an interview that it was her favorite episode of the show that she had written.<ref name=\"Convention\"/> She later expanded that the entry's \"full-on loopy\" quality made it humorous.<ref name=vult/> She noted that the episode was \"so funny to me, because what happened to [Michael] is so stupid.\"<ref name=vult>{{cite magazine|last=Martin |first=Denise |url=http://www.vulture.com/2012/08/mindy-kaling-on-the-end-of-the-office-and-her-favorite-episode-the-injury.html |title=Mindy Kaling on the End of The Office |magazine=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=August 22, 2012 |accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120105063559/http://www.nbc.com/the-office/episode-guide/season-2/58601/the-injury/episode-212/58834/ \"The Injury\"] at NBC.com\n*{{IMDb episode|0664528}}\n*{{Tv.com episode|589084}}\n\n{{The Office US Episodes}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Injury, The}}\n[[Category:The Office (American season 2) episodes]]\n[[Category:2006 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:Television episodes written by Mindy Kaling]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television episode\n| series       =[[The Office (American TV series)|The Office]]\n| season       =2\n| episode      =12\n| airdate      =January 12, 2006\n| production   =2011<ref name=\"prodnumbers\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/office/listings/|title=Shows A\u2013Z \u2013 Office, The on NBC|work=The Futon Critic|accessdate=January 25, 2013}}</ref>\n| director     =[[Bryan Gordon]]\n| writer       =[[Mindy Kaling]]\n| photographer =[[Randall Einhorn]]\n| editor       =[[Dean Holland]]\n| length = 22 minutes\n| guests       = *[[Leslie David Baker]] as [[Stanley Hudson]]\n*[[Brian Baumgartner]] as [[Kevin Malone]]\n*[[Kate Flannery]] as [[Meredith Palmer]]\n*[[Angela Kinsey]] as [[Angela Martin]]\n*[[Oscar Nunez]] as [[Oscar Martinez (The Office)|Oscar Martinez]]\n*[[Phyllis Smith]] as [[Phyllis Vance|Phyllis Lapin]]\n*Marcus A. York as [[List of The Office (American TV series) characters#Billy Merchant|Billy Merchant]]\n| season_article = The Office (American season 2)\n| episode_list =List of The Office (American TV series) episodes\n| season_list  =\n| prev         =[[Booze Cruise (The Office)|Booze Cruise]]\n| next         =[[The Secret (The Office)|The Secret]]\n}}\n\n\"'''The Injury'''\" is the twelfth episode of the [[The Office (U.S. season 2)|second season]] of the American [[comedy]] [[television program|television series]] ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]'', and the show's eighteenth episode overall. The episode was written by [[Mindy Kaling]], who also acts in the show as [[Kelly Kapoor]], and directed by [[Bryan Gordon]]. \"The Injury\" first aired in the United States on January 12, 2006 on [[NBC]]. The episode guest starred Marcus York as [[List of characters from The Office (US T.V. series)#Billy Merchant|Billy Merchant]].\n\nThe series depicts the everyday lives of office employees in the [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]] branch of the fictional [[Dunder Mifflin]] Paper Company. In the episode, [[Michael Scott (The Office)|Michael Scott]] ([[Steve Carell]]) accidentally burns his foot on his [[George Foreman Grill]], but insists on coming to work anyway. When none of his employees, except for [[Dwight Schrute]] ([[Rainn Wilson]]), help him, Michael feels under-appreciated. Meanwhile, Dwight starts acting strangely nice to everyone, especially [[Pam Beesly]] ([[Jenna Fischer]]).\n\n\"The Injury\" was originally conceived by [[Greg Daniels]] to be a humorous follow-up to the previous episode, \"[[Booze Cruise (The Office)|Booze Cruise]]\". According to [[B. J. Novak]], the episode started out as an idea in the writing room that just \"spun out of control\". The episode was originally going to be called \"My Grilled Foot\", but it was later changed when the writers decided the name was \"too weird\". \"The Injury\" received widespread acclaim from critics and is widely regarded by critics as one of the show's greatest episodes. The episode earned a Nielsen rating of 5.1 in the 18\u201349 demographic and was viewed by 10.3 million viewers, making it, at the time, the highest-rated episode of the series.\n\n==Plot==\n[[Michael Scott (The Office)|Michael Scott]] ([[Steve Carell]]) accidentally burns his foot while grilling [[bacon]] on his [[George Foreman Grill]], which he keeps next to his bed. After he makes a distress call to the office, [[Dwight Schrute]] ([[Rainn Wilson]]) comes to \"rescue\" him, but crashes his car into [[gatepost|a pole]]. Dwight becomes more easygoing and friendly to his co-workers. He and [[Pam Beesly]] ([[Jenna Fischer]]) strike up a friendship as a result.\n\nMichael becomes upset with the staff's lack of compassion towards his \"disability\", and brings in [[List of characters from The Office (US T.V. series)#Billy Merchant|Billy Merchant]] (Marcus A. York), the building's property manager who uses a [[wheelchair]], to discuss what it is like to be disabled. Billy leaves after Michael makes several offensive remarks, but not before pointing out to [[Jim Halpert]] ([[John Krasinski]]) that Dwight has suffered a [[concussion]] from his car crash.\n\nJim and Michael take Dwight to the hospital, where Michael insists that his burned foot is a more serious injury than Dwight's. Before they go, Pam bids \"goodbye\" to the concussed Dwight, aware that she will probably never see the good-natured version of Dwight Schrute ever again.\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Mindy Kaling at PaleyFest 2013.jpg|The episode was written by [[Mindy Kaling]], who called the episode her favorite that she had written.|200px|thumb|right]]\n\nThis episode was the second episode of the series directed by [[Bryan Gordon]].<ref name=\"episode\">{{Cite episode | title = The Injury | series = The Office | serieslink = The Office (U.S. TV series) | credits = [[Mindy Kaling]] (writer), [[Bryan Gordon]] (director) | network = NBC | airdate = January 12, 2006 | season = 2 | number = 12}}</ref> Gordon had previously directed the [[The Office (U.S. season 1)|first season]] episode \"[[The Alliance (The Office)|The Alliance]]\".<ref name=\"DVD2\">{{cite DVD notes |title=The Office: The Complete First Season |titlelink=The Office (American season 1) |origyear=2005 |others=[[Ken Kwapis]], et al |type=on-screen |publisher=[[NBC]]}}</ref> \"The Injury\" was written by [[Mindy Kaling]], who also acts for the show as customer service representative [[Kelly Kapoor]].<ref name=\"Mindy.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbc.com/The_Office/bios/mindy_kaling.shtml|title=Mindy Kaling|accessdate=June 26, 2008|last=|first=|coauthors=|date=|work=|publisher=NBC.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618054824/http://www.nbc.com/The_Office/bios/mindy_kaling.shtml|archivedate=June 18, 2008|df=}}</ref> After the character development that had occurred in the previous episode, \"[[Booze Cruise (The Office)|Booze Cruise]]\", Greg Daniels decided to create a more inane episode that involved \"Michael's grilled foot.\"<ref name=\"Convention\"/>\n\nWriter and actor [[B. J. Novak]] said the idea for \"Injury\" started out as an idea in the writing room that just \"spun out of control\".<ref name=\"Katy\">{{cite web|title=Katy Meets B.J.|url=http://www.officetally.com/bj-novak-duquesne-university|publisher=OfficeTally|accessdate=June 16, 2012|date=April 1, 2007}}</ref> The original plan was for Michael to have fallen asleep in the sun, while having sunblock all over him, except for his foot. According to BJ Novak, the episode was originally going to be called \"My Grilled Foot\", but writer Mindy Kaling thought it was \"too weird for people to tune in and watch that\".<ref name=\"Convention\">{{cite interview |last = The Office Cast|first = |title = The Office Convention 2007 Cast Q&A |year = 2007| location = ''The Office: Overtime'' | publisher = [[NBC]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=B.J. Novak answer 'Chair Model' questions|url=http://www.officetally.com/bj-novak-answers-chair-model-questions|publisher=OfficeTally|accessdate=13 December 2011}}</ref> Novak has described \"The Injury\" as one of his favorite episodes, and said of it, \"I don't think any other TV show would have made an episode from that starting point, and yet it was one of the funniest and most relatable episodes as it went on that we've ever had.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Yo |first=Michael |title=''The Office'': \"This Is Their Wedding Episode\" |work=[[E!]] |date=2009-04-30 |url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/watch_with_kristin/b121452_office_this_their_wedding_episode.html |accessdate=2009-05-17}}</ref>\n\nThe episode guest starred Marcus York, as the \"no-nonsense\" building manager for the Scranton business park. York described his character as \"just trying to do his job\".<ref name=interviewwithbilly/> York recalls being nervous during filming, and \"drawing a blank\" on his lines during the first 'run-through', because of his anxiousness around the cast members, but soon Marcus \"smoothed-out\".<ref name=\"TwoCents\">{{cite web|author=York, Marcus|date=June 16, 2006|url=http://keithp23.blogspot.com/2007/08/two-cents-five-questions-with_23.html|title=Two Cents & Five Questions With...|work=The Two Cents|accessdate=June 16, 2008}}</ref> After his portrayal of the character, York received several positive fan letters, who praised his performance as the straight man in a hectic work environment.<ref name=interviewwithbilly>{{cite magazine|last=Benet|first=Lorenzo|title=The Office Star's Own Health-Care Reform Mission|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20351156,00.html|magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=June 16, 2012|date=March 14, 2010}}</ref> John Krasinski said that the van scene was his favorite to shoot, and that it \"will go down in history as one of the most fun moments I've ever been a part of\".<ref name=\"Krasinski\">{{cite web|author=Krasinski, John|date=June 16, 2006|url=http://www.officetally.com/john-krasinski-chat-transcript|title=John Krasinski chat transcript|work=OfficeTally|accessdate=June 16, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural references==\nMichael reveals that he burned his foot on a [[George Foreman Grill]], a product promoted by [[George Foreman]], a former champion [[boxing|boxer]]. The \"Prism DuroSport\" that Pam received from Roy as a Christmas present serves as a [[Counterfeit consumer goods|knock off]] of the popular music device, the [[iPod]]. When Michael asks the office what his foot looks like, Stanley replies, \"[[Mail Boxes Etc.]]\", a reference to the name of a company absorbed by [[United Parcel Service|UPS]] in 2001.<ref name=\"Giant\"/>\n\nDuring Michael's seminar on famous disabled people, two pictures on the wall are of [[Tom Hanks]]: one from the 1994 film ''[[Forrest Gump]]'', and one from the 1988 film ''[[Big (film)|Big]]'', which Michael confuses for the 1993 film ''[[Philadelphia (film)|Philadelphia]]''.<ref name=\"Giant\"/><ref name=quotes>{{cite web|title=Michael Scott Quotes|url=http://www.tvfanatic.com/quotes/characters/michael-scott/page-92.html|publisher=TV Fanatic|accessdate=June 16, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131026150403/http://www.tvfanatic.com/quotes/characters/michael-scott/page-92.html|archive-date=October 26, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> During the scene, Kelly also name-drops [[Robert Loggia]]. In an attempt to get Dwight into Meredith's van, Jim tells him that they are going to [[Chuck E. Cheese]], to which Michael replies that he is \"so sick of\" the restaurant.<ref name=\"episode\"/>\n\n==Reception==\n\"The Injury\" originally aired on NBC in the United States on January 12, 2006.<ref name=seasontwoeps>{{cite web|title=The Office \u2013 Seasons \u2013 Season 2 \u2013 Episode Guide |url=http://www.nbc.com/the-office/episode-guide/season-2/58601/1/16/newest/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707145339/http://www.nbc.com/the-office/episode-guide/season-2/58601/1/16/newest/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 7, 2011 |publisher=[[NBC]] |accessdate=June 13, 2012 |df= }}</ref> The episode received a 5.1 rating/12% share among adults between the ages of 18 and 49. This means that it was seen by 5.1% of all 18- to 49-year-olds, and 12% of all 18- to 49-year-olds watching television at the time of the broadcast. The episode ranked as the third half-hour comedy during the week of January 16, and the series ranked as the fifteenth-highest-rated series out of 113 others, in the 18\u201349 demographic.<ref name=\"ratings\">{{cite press release |title=Jan. 18, 2006 Press Release (\"The Injury\")| archiveurl =http://www.officetally.com/the-office-nielsen-ratings/3| archivedate =October 10, 2008|url= http://nbcumv.com/release_detail.nbc/entertainment-20060118000000-nbcprimetimeresult.html|publisher=NBC|date=February 27, 2007|accessdate=June 12, 2012}}</ref> The episode was viewed by 10.3 million viewers,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Collins|first=Scott|title=NBC Enjoyed Thursday Night|journal=Los Angeles Times|date=January 13, 2006}}</ref> making it the highest-rated episode of ''The Office'' at the time, beating the series' [[Pilot (The Office)|pilot]], which received a Nielsen rating of only 5.0.<ref>[http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/ustv/a20222/american-office-an-early-ratings-hit.html  American 'Office' an early ratings hit] ''Digital Spy'', retrieved February 28, 2008</ref>\n\nAn encore presentation of the episode, on July 5, 2006, received a 1.8/6 rating and was viewed by over 3.9 million viewers: an increase by 29 percent of its lead-in audience.<ref name=\"ratings2\">{{cite press release |title=July 5, 2006 Press Release (\"Christmas Party,\" \"The Injury\")| archiveurl =http://www.officetally.com/the-office-nielsen-ratings/3| archivedate =October 10, 2008|url=http://nbcumv.com/release_detail.nbc/entertainment-20060705000000-039america039s.html|publisher=NBC|date=February 27, 2007|accessdate=June 12, 2012}}</ref> Another encore presentation on August 22, 2006 received a 2.0/6 rating, was viewed by 5.3 million viewers, retained 100 percent of its lead-in \"[[My Name is Earl]]\" audience, and ranked as the most-watched episode of ''The Office'' during the summer of 2006.<ref name=\"ratings3\">{{cite press release |title=Aug. 22, 2006 Press Release (\"The Injury\")| archiveurl =http://www.officetally.com/the-office-nielsen-ratings/3| archivedate =October 10, 2008|url=http://nbcumv.com/release_detail.nbc/entertainment-20060822000000-it039sagrandfi.html|publisher=NBC|date=February 27, 2007|accessdate=June 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSince its airing, \"The Injury\" has received critical acclaim from television critics. The scene featuring Dwight crashing his car received specific attention. ''[[IGN]]'' ranked the scene with Dwight getting in a car accident as its seventh-best moment in the first two seasons, noting that \"[t]he fact that this show can get such inspired and unusual comedy from what is essentially a puke joke is a testament to how clever ''The Office'' is.\"<ref name=\"Goldman\">Goldman, Eric & Zoromski, Brian (September 20, 2006) [http://tv.ign.com/articles/733/733879p1.html The Top 10 Moments from ''The Office''] ''[[IGN]]'', Retrieved June 16, 2008</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' named the same scene as the twentieth-funniest in ''The Office''{{'}}s first three seasons.<ref name=\"Thomas\">Thomas, Lindsey (October 17, 2007) [https://web.archive.org/web/20071020030009/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/16955952/the_25_greatest_moments_from_the_office/4 The 25 Greatest Moments from ''The Office''] ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', Retrieved June 16, 2008. Archived from [https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/16955952/the_25_greatest_moments_from_the_office/4 the original] on October 20, 2007.</ref> [[TV Squad]]'s Michael Sciannamea said that \"The Injury\" was \"another solid episode\" and that the \"show gets better with each and every week.\"<ref name=\"Sciannamea\">Sciannamea, Michael (January 13, 2006) [http://www.tvsquad.com/2006/01/13/the-office-the-injury/ ''The Office'': \"The Injury\"] TV Squad, Retrieved June 16, 2008</ref> M. Giant of [[Television Without Pity]] graded the episode with an \"A\u2013\".<ref name=\"Giant\">{{cite web|last=Giant|first=M.|date=January 12, 2006|url=http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/show/the_office/the_injury.php|title=The Injury|publisher=[[Television Without Pity]]|accessdate=June 17, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080421030324/http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/show/the_office/the_injury.php|archivedate=April 21, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> Francis Rizzo III from [[DVD Talk]] wrote positively of the episode and praised the performance of [[Rainn Wilson]] as Dwight and wrote that \"nothing he does compares\" to his performance in \"The Injury\". He called Wilson's performance as Dwight \"flat-out strange\" and noted that the episode, along with several others, \"wouldn't be nearly as entertaining\" without his character.<ref name=dvdtalk>{{cite web|last=Rizzo III|first=Francis|title=The Office \u2013 Season Two|url=http://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/23501/office-season-two-the/|publisher=[[DVD Talk]]|accessdate=June 12, 2012|date=September 12, 2006}}</ref> Mindy Kaling later stated in an interview that it was her favorite episode of the show that she had written.<ref name=\"Convention\"/> She later expanded that the entry's \"full-on loopy\" quality made it humorous.<ref name=vult/> She noted that the episode was \"so funny to me, because what happened to [Michael] is so stupid.\"<ref name=vult>{{cite magazine|last=Martin |first=Denise |url=http://www.vulture.com/2012/08/mindy-kaling-on-the-end-of-the-office-and-her-favorite-episode-the-injury.html |title=Mindy Kaling on the End of The Office |magazine=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=August 22, 2012 |accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120105063559/http://www.nbc.com/the-office/episode-guide/season-2/58601/the-injury/episode-212/58834/ \"The Injury\"] at NBC.com\n*{{IMDb episode|0664528}}\n*{{Tv.com episode|589084}}\n\n{{The Office US Episodes}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Injury, The}}\n[[Category:The Office (American season 2) episodes]]\n[[Category:2006 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:Television episodes written by Mindy Kaling]]\n", "name_user": "Gonnym", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Injury"}
{"title_page": "The Fire (The Office)", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:The Fire (''The Office'')}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox television episode\n| series       =[[The Office (American TV series)|The Office]]\n| season       =2\n| episode      =4\n| airdate      =October 11, 2005\n| production   =2001<ref name=\"prodnumbers\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/office/listings/|title=Shows A\u2013Z \u2013 Office, The on NBC|work=The Futon Critic|accessdate=January 25, 2013}}</ref>\n| director     =[[Ken Kwapis]]\n| writer       =[[B. J. Novak]]\n| music        =\"[[Everybody Hurts]]\" by [[R.E.M.]]\n| photographer =[[Randall Einhorn]]\n| editor       =[[David Rogers (editor)|David Rogers]]\n| length = 22 minutes\n| guests       =*[[David Denman]] as [[Roy Anderson (The Office)|Roy Anderson]]\n*[[Amy Adams]] as [[Katy Moore]]\n*[[Leslie David Baker]] as [[Stanley Hudson]]\n*[[Brian Baumgartner]] as [[Kevin Malone]]\n*[[Kate Flannery]] as [[Meredith Palmer]]\n*[[Mindy Kaling]] as [[Kelly Kapoor]]\n*[[Angela Kinsey]] as [[Angela Martin]]\n*[[Paul Lieberstein]] as [[Toby Flenderson]]\n*[[Oscar Nunez]] as [[Oscar Martinez (The Office)|Oscar Martinez]]\n*[[Phyllis Smith]] as [[Phyllis Vance|Phyllis Lapin]]\n| season_article = The Office (American season 2)\n| episode_list =List of The Office (American TV series) episodes\n| prev         =[[Office Olympics]]\n| next         =[[Halloween (The Office)|Halloween]]\n}}\n\n\"'''The Fire'''\" is the fourth episode of the second season of the American [[comedy]] [[television program|television series]] ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]'', and the show's tenth episode overall. Written by [[B. J. Novak]] and directed by [[Ken Kwapis]], the episode first aired in the United States on October 11, 2005 on [[NBC]]. The episode features [[Amy Adams]] as Jim's girlfriend, Katy.\n\nThe series depicts the everyday lives of office employees in the [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]] branch of the fictional [[Dunder Mifflin]] Paper Company. In the episode, [[Michael Scott (The Office)|Michael Scott]] ([[Steve Carell]]) takes it upon himself to teach [[Ryan Howard (The Office)|Ryan Howard]] ([[B. J. Novak]]) about business, but soon everyone is forced to evacuate the office due to a fire. While outside, Michael continues to show an interest in Ryan, causing [[Dwight Schrute]] ([[Rainn Wilson]]) to be jealous. Meanwhile, [[Jim Halpert]] ([[John Krasinski]]) organizes games to play outside.\n\nAccording to B. J. Novak, the episode was \"a fun one to film\". Although the cast and crew appear to be cold in the finished episode, \"The Fire\" was filmed in 100-degree weather; thus, the actors \"couldn't look hot\" and had to pretend to shiver. The firemen in the scene were played by actual firemen, and their costumes were designed in order to look like authentic Scranton firefighters.\n\n==Plot==\n[[Pam Beesly]] ([[Jenna Fischer]]) learns that [[Jim Halpert]] ([[John Krasinski]]) and [[List of characters from The Office (US T.V. series)#Katy Moore|Katy Moore]] ([[Amy Adams]]) have started dating. [[Michael Scott (The Office)|Michael Scott]] ([[Steve Carell]]) gives [[Ryan Howard (The Office)|Ryan Howard]] ([[B. J. Novak]]) a glowing checkpoint review. When Ryan expresses his interest in starting his own business someday, Michael takes it upon himself to teach Ryan the \"ten rules of business\". The fire alarm sounds, and while [[Dwight Schrute]] ([[Rainn Wilson]]) and [[Angela Martin]] ([[Angela Kinsey]]) both attempt to take charge of the evacuation, Michael pushes others out of the way in his escape out of the building.\n\nThe employees play games to pass the time, including \"Desert Island Picks\" and \"Who Would You Do?\" When Ryan reveals that he is attending business school at night, Michael becomes enamored of his newfound prot\u00e9g\u00e9. Dwight becomes noticeably jealous of Ryan's favor with Michael, and he is seen sulking in his car to the tune \"[[Everybody Hurts]]\" by [[R.E.M.]] When Michael mentions that he left his cell phone in the office, Dwight rushes back into the building to fetch it.\n\nMichael asks Ryan to call his cell phone to help Dwight find it. The phone rings, which happens to be in Michael's pocket. Dwight emerges, coughing, from the building and reveals that the fire was started by Ryan, who left a [[pita|cheese pita]] in the toaster-oven set to \"oven\" instead of \"toaster\". Dwight and Michael mock Ryan and dub him \"The Fire Guy\" by doing a song parody of the [[Billy Joel]] song \"[[We Didn't Start the Fire]]\".\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Amy Adams (29708985502) (cropped).jpg|thumb|[[Amy Adams]] guest starred in the episode, playing Katy.]]\n\n\"The Fire\" was the fourth episode of the series directed by [[Ken Kwapis]]. Kwapis had previously directed \"[[Pilot (The Office)|Pilot]]\", \"[[Diversity Day (The Office)|Diversity Day]]\", and \"[[Sexual Harassment (The Office)|Sexual Harassment]]\". \"The Fire\" was written by [[B. J. Novak]], who also acts on the show as [[Ryan Howard (The Office)|Ryan Howard]].<ref name=\"fire\"/> Novak had previously penned the episodes \"[[Diversity Day (The Office)|Diversity Day]]\" and \"[[Sexual Harassment (The Office)|Sexual Harassment]]\".<ref name=\"Novak\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbc.com/The_Office/bios/bj_novak.shtml |title=B.J. Novak |accessdate=June 27, 2008 |last= |first= |coauthors= |date= |work= |publisher=NBC.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080913133357/http://www.nbc.com/The_Office/bios/bj_novak.shtml |archivedate=September 13, 2008 |df= }}</ref> \"The Fire\" featured the second appearance of Katy, portrayed by [[Amy Adams]]. Adams thoroughly enjoyed her work on the show.<ref name=advocate/> In an interview with Advocate.com, she said, \"[''The Office''] was the best work experience. I loved that show and that cast so much. I don\u2019t know if they believe me, but every time I see them I\u2019m like, 'Oh my gosh, I\u2019ll do anything to come back.'\"<ref name=advocate>{{cite web|last=Voss |first=Brandon |title=Amy Adams: Big Gay Following |url=http://www.advocate.com/printArticle.aspx?id=22184 |publisher=Advocate.com |archiveurl=http://brandonvoss.com/blog/amy-adams-big-gay-following|archivedate=December 1, 2007|date=December 1, 2007}}</ref>\n\nNovak described the episode as \"a fun one to film\".<ref name=\"fire\"/> The episode was filmed in 100-degree weather, but according to cast member B. J. Novak, they \"couldn't look hot\". The area outside the building was shot in [[Van Nuys, California]] in what Novak called a \"bad area\": he later noted that they \"had to pretend we weren't scared, even though every car that is left next to our set overnight is stripped to the bone for parts.\"<ref name=\"fire\"/> Greg Daniels noted that during the filming of \"The Fire\", the cast and crew kept being interrupted by the sound of helicopters.<ref name=\"Convention\">{{cite interview |last           = The Office Cast|first          =  | subjectlink  = Gillian Anderson |title          = The Office Convention 2007 Cast Q&A |year           = 2007| location = ''The Office: Overtime'' | publisher = [[NBC]]}}</ref>  The firemen in the scene were played by actual firemen.<ref name=\"fire\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/bj-novak-office-40860.aspx |title=Which Office Stars Have the Write Stuff? |accessdate=July 30, 2008 |last=Novak |first=B. J. |date=October 11, 2005 |magazine=[[TV Guide]]}}</ref> The crew of ''The Office'' had someone in Scranton take photographs of local firefighters' uniforms, so the costumes would be accurate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.phillymag.com/articles/office_party/page4 |title=Office Party |accessdate=July 30, 2008 |last=Marchese |first=John |coauthors= |date=March 2007 |work= |publisher=[[Philadelphia Magazine]]}}</ref> However, in an interview with the ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'', Scranton firefighter Art Franklin pointed out that the uniform is actually tan, instead of the black ones seen on the show.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/06291/730750-237.stm |title=Scranton meets 'The Office' |accessdate=July 30, 2008 |last=Rouvalis |first=Christina |date=October 18, 2006 |newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural references==\nWhen lecturing Ryan, Michael compares himself to [[Yoda]] and [[Mr. Miyagi]]. When he later attempts to do a Yoda voice, Ryan misinterprets it as an impression of [[Fozzie Bear]] (ironically, both characters are portrayed by puppeteer [[Frank Oz]]). When Dwight is dejectedly listening to music in his car, he is playing \"[[Everybody Hurts]]\" by [[R.E.M.]] Dwight and Michael's \"Ryan Started the Fire\" is an thinly veiled song parody of the [[Billy Joel]] song \"[[We Didn't Start the Fire]]\".<ref name=\"Alli\"/>\n\nDuring the game of desert island, many of the employees reference specific films and books. Angela says she would take [[The Bible]], ''[[A Purpose Driven Life]]'', and ''[[The Da Vinci Code]]'', but only to burn the latter. Dwight notes that he would take the ''[[Physicians' Desk Reference]]'', but hollow it out and fill it with supplies; he also states we would bring ''[[Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone]]'' or ''[[Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban]]'' in case he got bored. Meredith later reveals that she would bring ''[[Legends of the Fall]]'', ''[[My Big Fat Greek Wedding]]'', ''[[Legally Blonde]]'', ''[[The Bridges of Madison County (film)|The Bridges of Madison County]]'', and \"just the pottery scene\" from [[Ghost (1990 film)|''Ghost'']] to watch. Pam picks ''[[Fargo (film)|Fargo]]'', ''[[Edward Scissorhands]]'', ''[[Dazed and Confused (film)|Dazed and Confused]]'', ''[[The Breakfast Club]]'', and ''[[The Princess Bride (film)|The Princess Bride]]''. After asking what Dwight would bring, he says ''[[The Crow (1994 film)|The Crow]]''.<ref name=\"Alli\"/>\n\n==Reception==\n\"The Fire\" originally aired on NBC in the United States on October 11, 2005.<ref name=seasontwoeps>{{cite web|title=The Office \u2013 Seasons \u2013 Season 2 \u2013 Episode Guide|url=http://www.nbc.com/the-office/episode-guide/season-2/58601/2/16/newest/|publisher=[[NBC]]|accessdate=June 13, 2012}}</ref> The episode was viewed by 7.6 million viewers and received a 3.7 rating/9% share among adults between the ages of 18 and 49. This means that it was seen by 3.7% of all 18- to 49-year-olds, and 9% of all 18- to 49-year-olds watching television at the time of the broadcast. The episode won its timeslot.<ref name=\"ratings\">{{cite press release |title=Oct. 18, 2005 Press Release (\"The Fire\")| archiveurl =http://www.officetally.com/the-office-nielsen-ratings/3| archivedate =October 10, 2008|url= http://nbcumv.com/release_detail.nbc/entertainment-20051018000000-nbcprimetimeresult.html|publisher=NBC|date=February 27, 2007|accessdate=June 12, 2012}}</ref> An encore presentation of the episode, on June 6, 2006, received 1.9 rating/6% share and was viewed by over 4.6 million viewers.<ref name=\"ratings2\">{{cite press release |title=June 6, 2006 Press Release (\"The Fire,\" \"Halloween,\" \"The Client,\" \"Performance Review\")| archiveurl =http://www.officetally.com/the-office-nielsen-ratings/3| archivedate =October 10, 2008|url=http://nbcumv.com/release_detail.nbc/entertainment-20060606000000-nbcprimetimeresult.html|publisher=NBC|date=February 27, 2007|accessdate=June 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\n\"The Fire\" received mostly positive reviews from critics. [[TV Squad]]'s Michael Sciannamea wrote that \"The Fire\" was \"another good episode.\" Sciannamea went on to write that \"show has definitely improved and it's nice to see the other characters emerge\".<ref name=\"Sciannamea\">{{cite web |url= http://www.tvsquad.com/2005/10/11/the-office-the-fire/ |title= ''The Office'': \"The Fire\" |accessdate=July 30, 2008 |last=Sciannamea |first=Michael |coauthors= |date=October 11, 2005 |publisher=[[TV Squad]]}}</ref> \"Miss Alli\" of [[Television Without Pity]] graded the episode with a \"B+\".<ref name=\"Alli\">{{cite web|url=http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/show/the_office/the_fire.php |title=The Fire |accessdate=July 30, 2008 |author=Miss Alli |coauthors= |date=October 11, 2005 |work= |publisher=[[Television Without Pity]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080421030319/http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/show/the_office/the_fire.php |archivedate=April 21, 2008 |df= }}</ref> Dwight's reinterpretation of \"We Didn't Start the Fire\" inspired fans of the office to make their own song parodies. One version, aptly titled \"Ryan Started the Fire\", lists several events from ''The Office'', much like the original. After posting the song, Margaret Lyons from ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' wrote, \"Yay for the Internet!\"<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Lyons|first=Margaret|title='The Office' fan video: 'Ryan started the fire'|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2009/02/19/clip-of-the-day/|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=June 13, 2012|date=February 19, 2009}}</ref>\n\nErik Adams of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' awarded the episode an \"A\u2013\", noting that \"'The Fire' is not the second season\u2019s funniest half-hour, but I love it for its simplicity.\"<ref name=avclub/> Writing that the episode bore similarities to a [[bottle episode]], he enjoyed the way that the conversations among the employees allowed the audience to more fully understand all of the individual characters better. Adams also praised the interaction between Carell and Novak, as well as the performance of Wilson, which he called \"unsettling\".<ref name=avclub>{{cite web|last=Adams|first=Erik|title='Office Olympics'/'The Fire' {{!}} The Office {{!}} TV Club|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/office-olympicsthe-fire,99523/|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[The Onion]]|accessdate=July 10, 2013|date=July 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://archive.today/20130129155413/http://www.nbc.com/the-office/episode-guide/season-2/58601/the-fire/episode-204/58643/ \"The Fire\"] at NBC.com\n*{{IMDb episode|0664527|The Fire}}\n*{{Tv.com episode|485040}}\n\n{{The Office US Episodes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fire, The}}\n[[Category:2005 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:Fire in fiction]]\n[[Category:The Office (American season 2) episodes]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:The Fire (''The Office'')}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox Television episode\n| series       =[[The Office (American TV series)|The Office]]\n| season       =2\n| episode      =4\n| airdate      =October 11, 2005\n| production   =2001<ref name=\"prodnumbers\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/office/listings/|title=Shows A\u2013Z \u2013 Office, The on NBC|work=The Futon Critic|accessdate=January 25, 2013}}</ref>\n| director     =[[Ken Kwapis]]\n| writer       =[[B. J. Novak]]\n| music        =\"[[Everybody Hurts]]\" by [[R.E.M.]]\n| photographer =[[Randall Einhorn]]\n| editor       =[[David Rogers (editor)|David Rogers]]\n| length = 22 minutes\n| guests       =*[[David Denman]] as [[Roy Anderson (The Office)|Roy Anderson]]\n*[[Amy Adams]] as [[Katy Moore]]\n*[[Leslie David Baker]] as [[Stanley Hudson]]\n*[[Brian Baumgartner]] as [[Kevin Malone]]\n*[[Kate Flannery]] as [[Meredith Palmer]]\n*[[Mindy Kaling]] as [[Kelly Kapoor]]\n*[[Angela Kinsey]] as [[Angela Martin]]\n*[[Paul Lieberstein]] as [[Toby Flenderson]]\n*[[Oscar Nunez]] as [[Oscar Martinez (The Office)|Oscar Martinez]]\n*[[Phyllis Smith]] as [[Phyllis Vance|Phyllis Lapin]]\n| season_article = The Office (American season 2)\n| episode_list =List of The Office (American TV series) episodes\n| season_list  =\n| prev         =[[Office Olympics]]\n| next         =[[Halloween (The Office)|Halloween]]\n}}\n\n\"'''The Fire'''\" is the fourth episode of the second season of the American [[comedy]] [[television program|television series]] ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]'', and the show's tenth episode overall. Written by [[B. J. Novak]] and directed by [[Ken Kwapis]], the episode first aired in the United States on October 11, 2005 on [[NBC]]. The episode features [[Amy Adams]] as Jim's girlfriend, Katy.\n\nThe series depicts the everyday lives of office employees in the [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]] branch of the fictional [[Dunder Mifflin]] Paper Company. In the episode, [[Michael Scott (The Office)|Michael Scott]] ([[Steve Carell]]) takes it upon himself to teach [[Ryan Howard (The Office)|Ryan Howard]] ([[B. J. Novak]]) about business, but soon everyone is forced to evacuate the office due to a fire. While outside, Michael continues to show an interest in Ryan, causing [[Dwight Schrute]] ([[Rainn Wilson]]) to be jealous. Meanwhile, [[Jim Halpert]] ([[John Krasinski]]) organizes games to play outside.\n\nAccording to B. J. Novak, the episode was \"a fun one to film\". Although the cast and crew appear to be cold in the finished episode, \"The Fire\" was filmed in 100-degree weather; thus, the actors \"couldn't look hot\" and had to pretend to shiver. The firemen in the scene were played by actual firemen, and their costumes were designed in order to look like authentic Scranton firefighters.\n\n==Plot==\n[[Pam Beesly]] ([[Jenna Fischer]]) learns that [[Jim Halpert]] ([[John Krasinski]]) and [[List of characters from The Office (US T.V. series)#Katy Moore|Katy Moore]] ([[Amy Adams]]) have started dating. [[Michael Scott (The Office)|Michael Scott]] ([[Steve Carell]]) gives [[Ryan Howard (The Office)|Ryan Howard]] ([[B. J. Novak]]) a glowing checkpoint review. When Ryan expresses his interest in starting his own business someday, Michael takes it upon himself to teach Ryan the \"ten rules of business\". The fire alarm sounds, and while [[Dwight Schrute]] ([[Rainn Wilson]]) and [[Angela Martin]] ([[Angela Kinsey]]) both attempt to take charge of the evacuation, Michael pushes others out of the way in his escape out of the building.\n\nThe employees play games to pass the time, including \"Desert Island Picks\" and \"Who Would You Do?\" When Ryan reveals that he is attending business school at night, Michael becomes enamored of his newfound prot\u00e9g\u00e9. Dwight becomes noticeably jealous of Ryan's favor with Michael, and he is seen sulking in his car to the tune \"[[Everybody Hurts]]\" by [[R.E.M.]] When Michael mentions that he left his cell phone in the office, Dwight rushes back into the building to fetch it.\n\nMichael asks Ryan to call his cell phone to help Dwight find it. The phone rings, which happens to be in Michael's pocket. Dwight emerges, coughing, from the building and reveals that the fire was started by Ryan, who left a [[pita|cheese pita]] in the toaster-oven set to \"oven\" instead of \"toaster\". Dwight and Michael mock Ryan and dub him \"The Fire Guy\" by doing a song parody of the [[Billy Joel]] song \"[[We Didn't Start the Fire]]\".\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Amy Adams (29708985502) (cropped).jpg|thumb|[[Amy Adams]] guest starred in the episode, playing Katy.]]\n\n\"The Fire\" was the fourth episode of the series directed by [[Ken Kwapis]]. Kwapis had previously directed \"[[Pilot (The Office)|Pilot]]\", \"[[Diversity Day (The Office)|Diversity Day]]\", and \"[[Sexual Harassment (The Office)|Sexual Harassment]]\". \"The Fire\" was written by [[B. J. Novak]], who also acts on the show as [[Ryan Howard (The Office)|Ryan Howard]].<ref name=\"fire\"/> Novak had previously penned the episodes \"[[Diversity Day (The Office)|Diversity Day]]\" and \"[[Sexual Harassment (The Office)|Sexual Harassment]]\".<ref name=\"Novak\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbc.com/The_Office/bios/bj_novak.shtml |title=B.J. Novak |accessdate=June 27, 2008 |last= |first= |coauthors= |date= |work= |publisher=NBC.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080913133357/http://www.nbc.com/The_Office/bios/bj_novak.shtml |archivedate=September 13, 2008 |df= }}</ref> \"The Fire\" featured the second appearance of Katy, portrayed by [[Amy Adams]]. Adams thoroughly enjoyed her work on the show.<ref name=advocate/> In an interview with Advocate.com, she said, \"[''The Office''] was the best work experience. I loved that show and that cast so much. I don\u2019t know if they believe me, but every time I see them I\u2019m like, 'Oh my gosh, I\u2019ll do anything to come back.'\"<ref name=advocate>{{cite web|last=Voss |first=Brandon |title=Amy Adams: Big Gay Following |url=http://www.advocate.com/printArticle.aspx?id=22184 |publisher=Advocate.com |archiveurl=http://brandonvoss.com/blog/amy-adams-big-gay-following|archivedate=December 1, 2007|date=December 1, 2007}}</ref>\n\nNovak described the episode as \"a fun one to film\".<ref name=\"fire\"/> The episode was filmed in 100-degree weather, but according to cast member B. J. Novak, they \"couldn't look hot\". The area outside the building was shot in [[Van Nuys, California]] in what Novak called a \"bad area\": he later noted that they \"had to pretend we weren't scared, even though every car that is left next to our set overnight is stripped to the bone for parts.\"<ref name=\"fire\"/> Greg Daniels noted that during the filming of \"The Fire\", the cast and crew kept being interrupted by the sound of helicopters.<ref name=\"Convention\">{{cite interview |last           = The Office Cast|first          =  | subjectlink  = Gillian Anderson |title          = The Office Convention 2007 Cast Q&A |year           = 2007| location = ''The Office: Overtime'' | publisher = [[NBC]]}}</ref>  The firemen in the scene were played by actual firemen.<ref name=\"fire\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/bj-novak-office-40860.aspx |title=Which Office Stars Have the Write Stuff? |accessdate=July 30, 2008 |last=Novak |first=B. J. |date=October 11, 2005 |magazine=[[TV Guide]]}}</ref> The crew of ''The Office'' had someone in Scranton take photographs of local firefighters' uniforms, so the costumes would be accurate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.phillymag.com/articles/office_party/page4 |title=Office Party |accessdate=July 30, 2008 |last=Marchese |first=John |coauthors= |date=March 2007 |work= |publisher=[[Philadelphia Magazine]]}}</ref> However, in an interview with the ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'', Scranton firefighter Art Franklin pointed out that the uniform is actually tan, instead of the black ones seen on the show.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/06291/730750-237.stm |title=Scranton meets 'The Office' |accessdate=July 30, 2008 |last=Rouvalis |first=Christina |date=October 18, 2006 |newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural references==\nWhen lecturing Ryan, Michael compares himself to [[Yoda]] and [[Mr. Miyagi]]. When he later attempts to do a Yoda voice, Ryan misinterprets it as an impression of [[Fozzie Bear]] (ironically, both characters are portrayed by puppeteer [[Frank Oz]]). When Dwight is dejectedly listening to music in his car, he is playing \"[[Everybody Hurts]]\" by [[R.E.M.]] Dwight and Michael's \"Ryan Started the Fire\" is an thinly veiled song parody of the [[Billy Joel]] song \"[[We Didn't Start the Fire]]\".<ref name=\"Alli\"/>\n\nDuring the game of desert island, many of the employees reference specific films and books. Angela says she would take [[The Bible]], ''[[A Purpose Driven Life]]'', and ''[[The Da Vinci Code]]'', but only to burn the latter. Dwight notes that he would take the ''[[Physicians' Desk Reference]]'', but hollow it out and fill it with supplies; he also states we would bring ''[[Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone]]'' or ''[[Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban]]'' in case he got bored. Meredith later reveals that she would bring ''[[Legends of the Fall]]'', ''[[My Big Fat Greek Wedding]]'', ''[[Legally Blonde]]'', ''[[The Bridges of Madison County (film)|The Bridges of Madison County]]'', and \"just the pottery scene\" from [[Ghost (1990 film)|''Ghost'']] to watch. Pam picks ''[[Fargo (film)|Fargo]]'', ''[[Edward Scissorhands]]'', ''[[Dazed and Confused (film)|Dazed and Confused]]'', ''[[The Breakfast Club]]'', and ''[[The Princess Bride (film)|The Princess Bride]]''. After asking what Dwight would bring, he says ''[[The Crow (1994 film)|The Crow]]''.<ref name=\"Alli\"/>\n\n==Reception==\n\"The Fire\" originally aired on NBC in the United States on October 11, 2005.<ref name=seasontwoeps>{{cite web|title=The Office \u2013 Seasons \u2013 Season 2 \u2013 Episode Guide|url=http://www.nbc.com/the-office/episode-guide/season-2/58601/2/16/newest/|publisher=[[NBC]]|accessdate=June 13, 2012}}</ref> The episode was viewed by 7.6 million viewers and received a 3.7 rating/9% share among adults between the ages of 18 and 49. This means that it was seen by 3.7% of all 18- to 49-year-olds, and 9% of all 18- to 49-year-olds watching television at the time of the broadcast. The episode won its timeslot.<ref name=\"ratings\">{{cite press release |title=Oct. 18, 2005 Press Release (\"The Fire\")| archiveurl =http://www.officetally.com/the-office-nielsen-ratings/3| archivedate =October 10, 2008|url= http://nbcumv.com/release_detail.nbc/entertainment-20051018000000-nbcprimetimeresult.html|publisher=NBC|date=February 27, 2007|accessdate=June 12, 2012}}</ref> An encore presentation of the episode, on June 6, 2006, received 1.9 rating/6% share and was viewed by over 4.6 million viewers.<ref name=\"ratings2\">{{cite press release |title=June 6, 2006 Press Release (\"The Fire,\" \"Halloween,\" \"The Client,\" \"Performance Review\")| archiveurl =http://www.officetally.com/the-office-nielsen-ratings/3| archivedate =October 10, 2008|url=http://nbcumv.com/release_detail.nbc/entertainment-20060606000000-nbcprimetimeresult.html|publisher=NBC|date=February 27, 2007|accessdate=June 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\n\"The Fire\" received mostly positive reviews from critics. [[TV Squad]]'s Michael Sciannamea wrote that \"The Fire\" was \"another good episode.\" Sciannamea went on to write that \"show has definitely improved and it's nice to see the other characters emerge\".<ref name=\"Sciannamea\">{{cite web |url= http://www.tvsquad.com/2005/10/11/the-office-the-fire/ |title= ''The Office'': \"The Fire\" |accessdate=July 30, 2008 |last=Sciannamea |first=Michael |coauthors= |date=October 11, 2005 |publisher=[[TV Squad]]}}</ref> \"Miss Alli\" of [[Television Without Pity]] graded the episode with a \"B+\".<ref name=\"Alli\">{{cite web|url=http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/show/the_office/the_fire.php |title=The Fire |accessdate=July 30, 2008 |author=Miss Alli |coauthors= |date=October 11, 2005 |work= |publisher=[[Television Without Pity]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080421030319/http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/show/the_office/the_fire.php |archivedate=April 21, 2008 |df= }}</ref> Dwight's reinterpretation of \"We Didn't Start the Fire\" inspired fans of the office to make their own song parodies. One version, aptly titled \"Ryan Started the Fire\", lists several events from ''The Office'', much like the original. After posting the song, Margaret Lyons from ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' wrote, \"Yay for the Internet!\"<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Lyons|first=Margaret|title='The Office' fan video: 'Ryan started the fire'|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2009/02/19/clip-of-the-day/|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=June 13, 2012|date=February 19, 2009}}</ref>\n\nErik Adams of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' awarded the episode an \"A\u2013\", noting that \"'The Fire' is not the second season\u2019s funniest half-hour, but I love it for its simplicity.\"<ref name=avclub/> Writing that the episode bore similarities to a [[bottle episode]], he enjoyed the way that the conversations among the employees allowed the audience to more fully understand all of the individual characters better. Adams also praised the interaction between Carell and Novak, as well as the performance of Wilson, which he called \"unsettling\".<ref name=avclub>{{cite web|last=Adams|first=Erik|title='Office Olympics'/'The Fire' {{!}} The Office {{!}} TV Club|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/office-olympicsthe-fire,99523/|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[The Onion]]|accessdate=July 10, 2013|date=July 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://archive.today/20130129155413/http://www.nbc.com/the-office/episode-guide/season-2/58601/the-fire/episode-204/58643/ \"The Fire\"] at NBC.com\n*{{IMDb episode|0664527|The Fire}}\n*{{Tv.com episode|485040}}\n\n{{The Office US Episodes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fire, The}}\n[[Category:2005 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:Fire in fiction]]\n[[Category:The Office (American season 2) episodes]]\n", "name_user": "Gonnym", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Fire_(The_Office)"}
